    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "183cb9ec_2699473e",
        "filename": "results/README.md",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 16,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-01T20:46:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Right now, tagging with \"stable\" is meant to be done in `make deploy`, so `image-label` is just whatever description with which the user wants to annotate.\n\nFor instance, let\u0027s say I have two branches with changes FOO (with commit hash f00d) and BAR (with commit hash baad) committed, respectively. I might label them `with-change-foo` and `with-change-bar`, and they\u0027d both /also/ be tagged `f00d` and `baad`, respectively.\n\nThen on deployment, if I decided I wanted to deploy f00d, I could say `make deploy LABEL\u003dwith-change-foo`.\n\nThese retagging shenanigans aren\u0027t fantastic.\n\nVadim mentioned manually changing the deployment, specifically, \"[via] manual commit to the repository with k8s configs\". I can adapt that into here by getting rid of the \"stable\" label.\n\nThoughts?",
      "parentUuid": "8f32717e_f4c6957a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 16,
        "startChar": 22,
        "endLine": 16,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "0852fcdbbdaf0d92df8707c81aab4e86cde01488",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "043ae2df_610d4bba",
        "filename": "results/README.md",
